1. What is Spring Data JPA?

Theory
Spring Data JPA is a part of the larger Spring Data family, designed to simplify data access
layers in Java applications. It builds on top of the Java Persistence API (JPA) and provides
a repository abstraction layer, making it easier to implement data access with minimal
boilerplate code.

(i) JPA is a Java specification for managing, persisting, and accessing data between Java
objects and relational databases.
(ii) Spring Data JPA provides an additional layer that automates repository creation, query
generation, and integrates seamlessly with Spring’s ecosystem.

2. Advantages of Spring Data JPA:

a. Simplified Repository Interface

Theory:
You only need to define an interface for your repository, and Spring Data JPA provides the
implementation at runtime.

Implementation:

import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;

public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    // No implementation needed!
}

JpaRepository provides CRUD operations, pagination, and more out of the box.

b. Query Derivation

Theory:
Spring Data JPA can generate queries from method names in your repository interface. This
means you don’t have to write SQL or JPQL for simple queries.

Implementation:

List<User> findByLastName(String lastName);
User findByEmail(String email);
List<User> findByAgeGreaterThan(int age);

The method name tells Spring Data JPA how to generate the query.

c. Transaction Management

Theory:
Spring Data JPA integrates with Spring’s transaction management. By default, repository
methods are transactional.

Implementation:

@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @Transactional
    public void updateUser(User user) {
        userRepository.save(user);
    }
}

The @Transactional annotation ensures that the method runs within a transaction.

In simple terms, when a method is annotated with @Transactional in Spring, it means that all
the operations inside that method are executed as a single unit of work—a transaction. If
everything inside the method completes successfully, the changes are saved (committed) to the
database. If any part of the method fails (for example, an exception is thrown), all changes
made during that method are undone (rolled back), so the database remains unchanged by that
method call.

d. Integration with JPA/Hibernate

Theory:
Spring Data JPA works on top of JPA, and Hibernate is the most common JPA implementation.
You can use JPA annotations in your entities, and Spring Data JPA will handle the rest.

Implementation:

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    private String name;
    private String email;
    // getters and setters
}

Annotate your classes with JPA annotations (@Entity, @Id, etc.).
Spring Data JPA will use Hibernate (or another JPA provider) under the hood.